   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "participant-pattern-comparison-interpretation",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 14 Interpretation of Participant Pattern Comparison\n",
    "\n",
    "**Significance testing**\n",
    "Two kinds of participant-level checks were used here.\n",
    "- First, paired-samples t-tests tested whether the same participants changed in their **overall mean**, **topic means**, or **cue means** across datasets.\n",
    "- Second, explicit **pattern-agreement** metrics tested whether participants kept the same preference direction across datasets.\n",
    "\n",
    "For topic and cue patterns, agreement was quantified with:\n",
    "- **exact agreement proportion**\n",
    "- **Cohen's kappa**\n",
    "- a one-sided **binomial test** asking whether directional agreement was better than chance\n",
    "\n",
    "For condition patterns, agreement was quantified in two ways:\n",
    "- pairwise directional agreement for `latent vs recent`, `latent vs new`, and `recent vs new`\n",
    "- exact agreement on the full three-condition rank ordering\n",
    "\n",
    "**Results**\n",
    "- **Overall mean believability** was significantly lower in the **TruthSeeker data** (3.038) than in the **LLM data** (3.208), `t(9) = -3.48`, raw `p = .007`, Bonferroni-corrected `p_adj = .035`.\n",
    "- **Health** means were also lower in the **TruthSeeker data** (3.033) than in the **LLM data** (3.375), `t(9) = -2.41`, raw `p = .039`, but this was **not** significant after correction (`p_adj = .315`).\n",
    "- **Central** cue means were lower in the **TruthSeeker data** (3.083) than in the **LLM data** (3.392), `t(9) = -2.27`, raw `p = .050`, but this was **not** significant after correction (`p_adj = .398`).\n",
    "- **Technology** means were essentially unchanged across datasets (both 3.042), and **peripheral** cue means were also very similar (3.025 vs 2.992); neither comparison was significant.\n",
    "- For **topic preference direction** (`health > tech` vs `tech > health`), exact agreement was **40%** and Cohen's kappa was **-0.09**, showing no reliable participant-level stability of topic preference direction.\n",
    "- For **cue preference direction** (`central > peripheral` vs `peripheral > central`), exact agreement was **60%** and Cohen's kappa was **0.23**, which is only weak agreement and was not clearly above chance.\n",
    "- For **condition pattern**, the strongest pairwise stability was in `latent vs recent` with **80%** exact agreement and **kappa = 0.63**. Full three-condition rank agreement was **60%** with **kappa = 0.47**.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Interpretation**\n",
    "At the participant level, the **TruthSeeker data** are reliably lower overall than the **LLM data** for the same participants. But if the goal is to claim that the same participant keeps the same detailed preference pattern, the evidence is mixed: topic-direction agreement is weak, cue-direction agreement is modest, and condition ordering is more stable than topic or cue patterning but still not perfect.\n"
   ]
  },
