   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "participant-condition-comparison-md",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 15 Participant-Level Condition Comparison\n",
    "\n",
    "**Significance testing**\n",
    "The same 10 overlapping participants were analysed with a two-factor repeated-measures ANOVA:\n",
    "- `form`: **LLM data** vs **TruthSeeker data**\n",
    "- `condition`: `latent`, `recent`, `new`\n",
    "\n",
    "Bonferroni-corrected paired-samples t-tests then compared **TruthSeeker** versus **LLM** participant means separately within each condition.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Results**\n",
    "- There was a significant **main effect of form**, `F(1, 9) = 9.56`, `p = .013`, `eta_p^2 = 0.515`, showing that ratings were lower overall in the **TruthSeeker data** than in the **LLM data**.\n",
    "- There was also a significant **main effect of condition**, `F(2, 18) = 3.70`, `p = .045`, `eta_p^2 = 0.291`.\n",
    "- The **form x condition interaction** was not significant, `F(2, 18) = 0.18`, `p = .834`, `eta_p^2 = 0.020`, so the overall dataset shift did not differ reliably across `latent`, `recent`, and `new`.\n",
    "- In the Bonferroni-corrected follow-up tests, only the **recent** condition showed a significant participant-level drop from **LLM** (3.378) to **TruthSeeker** (3.188), `t(9) = -3.42`, `p_adj = .023`.\n",
    "- The **latent** comparison (3.200 vs 3.075) and the **new** comparison (3.000 vs 2.850) were not significant after correction.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Interpretation**\n",
    "The participant-level condition pattern is broadly similar across datasets, but the **TruthSeeker data** are shifted downward overall. The clearest reliable participant-level change is in the **recent** condition, where the same participants rated items lower in **TruthSeeker** than in **LLM**.\n"
   ]
